SUBJECT_DESCRIPTION: Pencil sketch and watercolour of Rhododendron falconeri by Joseph Hooker. Sketch formed the basis for W. H. Fitch's lithographs originally published in The Rhododendrons of Sikkim-Himalaya, 1849.
DISCOVERYASSISTANCE_KEYWORDS: Hooker, Joseph Hooker, art, biological, biology, botanical, botanical illustration, botany, plant, flowers, foliage, identifier, illustration, identity, leaf, leaves, nature, plant, plant organ, sketch, species, structure, study, vascular plant, vegetation, brown, green, rhododendron falconeri, Sikkim-Himalaya, plant collector
SUBJECT_ADDITIONALINFO: Hooker encountered Rhododendron falconeri during his ascent of Mount Tonglo. Hooker wrote: R. falconeri, in point of foliage the most superb of all the Himalayan species, with trunks thirty feet high, and branches bearing at their ends only leaves eighteen inches long: these are deep green above and covered beneath with a rich brown down.' Artist from England.

SUBJECT_DESCRIPTION: Field sketch of Rhododendron setosum by Joseph Hooker.
DISCOVERYASSISTANCE_KEYWORDS: Fitch, Himalaya, Hooker, Joseph Hooker, Rhododendron setosum, Sikkim, W. H. Fitch, art, biological, biology, botanical, botanical illustration, botany, flower, flowering plant, flowers, foliage, identifier, illustration, identity, leaf, leaves, magenta, nature, pink, plant, plant organ, sketch, species, structure, study, vascular plant, vegetation
SUBJECT_ADDITIONALINFO: The field sketches Joseph Hooker created formed the basis for Fitch's lithographs which were originally published in J. D. Hooker, The Rhododendrons of Sikkim-Himalaya, 1849. Hooker found Rhododendron setosum growing at altitudes above 13,000 feet, and noted: 'after hot sunshine, [it] fills the atmosphere with its powerful aroma, too heavy by far to be agreeable; and it is indeed a sad aggravation to the discomforts of toiling in the rarified medium it inhabits. Covering, as it does, extensive moorland tracts and rocky slopes, the brilliant red purple of its flowers renders it a charming and most lovely object.' Artist from England.

SUBJECT_DESCRIPTION: Sketch of Donkia Pass by Hooker (below) taken from Hooker's Himalayan notebooks, sheet 76, (above) watercolour of the same image by Walter Hood Fitch.
DISCOVERYASSISTANCE_KEYWORDS: Hooker, Joseph Hooker, art, sketch, botanical, botany, plant, flowers, foliage, identifier, illustration, nature, plant, sketch, species, mountain range, mountain, landscape, Himalaya, Walter Hood Fitch, W. H. Fitch, watercolour, graphite
SUBJECT_ADDITIONALINFO: When Joseph Hooker reached the Donkia Pass and saw the lake around the Cholamoo lakes, he wrote 'though my solitary situation rendered it doubly impressive to me, I doubt whether the world contains any scene with more sublime associations than this calm sheet of water, 17,000 feet above the sea, with the shadows of mountains 22, 000 to 24, 000 feet high, sleeping on its bosom.'

SUBJECT_ADDITIONALINFO: Joseph took careful measurements of many of the mountains he ascended: 'I have introduced angular heights, and been precise in my details, because the vagueness with which all terms are usually applied to the apparent altitude and steepness of mountains and precipices, is apt to give false impressions.' SUBJECT_DESCRIPTION: Pencil sketch by Hooker and watercolour by Fitch of Choonjerma Pass, Nepal.
DISCOVERYASSISTANCE_KEYWORDS: Hooker, Joseph Hooker, Walter Hood Fitch, art, identifier, illustration, identity, nature, sketch, structure, study, mountain, clouds, mist, mountain range, brown, blue, white, watercolour, graphite, pencil, Himalaya, Nepal, Mount Everest, Choonjerma Pass, Himalayan notebooks, peak
SUBJECT_ADDITIONALINFO: Joseph Hooker sketched the view from the Choonjerma Pass (below) in Nepal and it was later reproduced in watercolour by Walter Hood Fitch (above) for the published Himalayan Journals. The peak marked 'very high snows NNW' is believed to be Everest (or Mount Chomolungma as it is known locally), and this drawing, which dates from 1848, may be the earliest western illustration of the world's highest mountain.
